<% content_for(:title, "Chapter #{@chapter.position}: #{@chapter.title} — #{@book.title}") %>

<%= render "shared/page_header" %>

<div class="flex flex-col gap-10 lg:flex-row lg:items-start lg:gap-12">
  <%= render "toc", chapters: @chapters, active_chapter: @chapter.position %>

  <article class="min-w-0 flex-1 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm sm:p-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-slate-500">
      <%= link_to "Overview", books_coffeeshop_path, class: "font-medium text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-500" %>
      <span class="mx-1 text-slate-300" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span class="text-slate-600">Chapter <%= @chapter.position %> of <%= @chapters.size %></span>
    </p>

    <h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl">
      <%= @chapter.title %>
    </h1>

    <div class="mt-8 max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
        This is mock body copy for chapter <%= @chapter.position %>. Pretend your head barista leaned over during cleanup and
        said: “Here’s what actually matters about <%= @chapter.title.downcase %>—ignore the influencer stuff.”
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">The short version</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
        Operators win when defaults are boring: the dial-in notebook lives in one place, the mop bucket route never fights
        the pastry restock, and the POS reports get read on the same day every week. This chapter gathers those defaults into
        a single page your leads can riff on—not a binder nobody opens.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Three decisions to lock</h2>
      <ul class="mt-3 list-inside list-decimal space-y-2 leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
        <li>What metric you glance at daily (throughput, average ticket, waste—pick one).</li>
        <li>Who owns the checklist when the owner isn’t on the floor.</li>
        <li>What you refuse to add to the menu until margins are proven.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Try this on Monday</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
        Block fifteen minutes before open. Walk the line a guest would walk: door, menu legibility, dirty glassware, syrup
        fingerprints, trash visibility. Fix the first ugly thing you see with tools that already live on bar—no “we’ll order
        that later” unless safety demands it.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">If you only remember one line</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 rounded-xl border border-indigo-100 bg-indigo-50/80 px-4 py-3 text-indigo-950 leading-relaxed">
        Consistency beats cleverness: guests notice when the room feels calm, not when you added a fourth signature drink
        nobody ordered.
      </p>
    </div>

    <nav class="mt-12 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-between gap-4 border-t border-slate-200 pt-8 text-sm font-medium" aria-label="Chapter pagination">
      <% if (prev_ch = @chapters.find { |c| c.position == @chapter.position - 1 }) %>
        <%= link_to "← Previous chapter",
              books_coffeeshop_chapter_path(chapter: prev_ch.position),
              class: "text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-500" %>
      <% else %>
        <span class="text-slate-400">← Previous chapter</span>
      <% end %>

      <% if (next_ch = @chapters.find { |c| c.position == @chapter.position + 1 }) %>
        <%= link_to "Next chapter →",
              books_coffeeshop_chapter_path(chapter: next_ch.position),
              class: "text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-500" %>
      <% else %>
        <span class="text-slate-400">Next chapter →</span>
      <% end %>
    </nav>
  </article>
</div>
